helpdesk-ticket.subject: OpenHAB Web Access Issues
helpdesk-ticket.description:
This message is a follow up to one I sent earlier today and is in direct response to a message I got on my MSOE voice mail from James.
James raised the issue of my problem being related to VPN/torrent blocking by MSOE. I suppose this is possible, if such blocking blocks all traffic on port 8080. However, what I’m trying to do does not directly involve BPN or torrents. The OpenHAB software simply presents its main UI as a web page on port 8080. It is normally run on a free standing machine that users access over the internet via any webkit based browser. There should be no need for VPN.
What I’m trying to do, is to run it on my MSOE laptop and also access its UI using a browser running on my laptop. As I understand it, this should be possible using localhost as the URL for the connection. However, I’m far from expert in this area, so I really don’t know what is possible.
Dr. Tritt

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi thomasbe, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6040
I am showing that you are being continuously locked out. If you are able to receive this email I have a few suggestions. Your password was changed about a month ago. Something is probably trying to log you in remotely such as a program, browser, or network.
1. If you are using email on your phone, you need to update your password in account settings. 2. If you use GlobalProtect, You need to update the password in the edit: settings menu. 3. One of your old networks is trying to log you in to your old password. 4. A browser, such as chrome, has a stored password that is being used to try to log you in somewhere that is expired. 5. Outlook on your desktop may also have an old password. To change this click start, type credential manager and click on it, find the account that starts with ms.outlook, then click the dropdown and remove from vault. After this, you need to reopen outlook and it will prompt you for a new password.
If all of these fail, you may also come in to the helpdesk on the third floor of the CC or call us at 414.277.7288
We seem to have the wrong number for you and are unsure when you will get this email if at all, so I am marking this issue as resolved. If you have any more issues you can call us or email us. Have a nice day.
James Windorff Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi thomasbe,

Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6040

I am showing that you are being continuously locked out. If you are able to receive this email I have a few suggestions. 
Your password was changed about a month ago. Something is probably trying to log you in remotely such as a program, browser, or network.

1. If you are using email on your phone, you need to update your password in account settings.
2. If you use GlobalProtect, You need to update the password in the edit: settings menu.
3. One of your old networks is trying to log you in to your old password.
4. A browser, such as chrome, has a stored password that is being used to try to log you in somewhere that is expired.
5. Outlook on your desktop may also have an old password. To change this click start, type credential manager and click on it, find the account that starts with ms.outlook, then click the dropdown and remove from vault. After this, you need to reopen outlook and it will prompt you for a new password.

If all of these fail, you may also come in to the helpdesk on the third floor of the CC or call us at 414.277.7288

We seem to have the wrong number for you and are unsure when you will get this email if at all, so I am marking this issue as resolved.
If you have any more issues you can call us or email us.
Have a nice day.

James Windorff
Helpdesk Technician

414 277 7288

Dear MSOE Faculty and Staff,
In this ongoing series, Andy Holmes, Instructional Technologist, under the production of Ben Harris, Director of Desktop Management, will be delivering technology tips and best practice . This is an effort to drive high levels of performance and to ensure that the staff and faculty have what they need for daily success!
In this short, powerful video, you will learn some of the shocking facts about how much paper is consumed each quarter at a small school. You will also find some useful tips to conserve paper, such as:
* ​printing in duplex can save as many as 9 trees * decreasing font size by -1 can cut paper use by 18% * uploading documents to Blackboard can sharply reduce the amount of pages used per class Instructors can start by uploading the class syllabus, rather than printing a copy for every student. Since students have a computer, they have the ability to view online, or they can make the decision to print a copy.
Paper is an essential tool for education, and we certainly do not believe you will be completely paper-free; however, it is our hope that you will think carefully before you print, balancing the need for physical copies with the possibility of online delivery.
You can find instructions for uploading your syllabus, as well as other helpful Blackboard tips from the Blackboard Best Practices Course<https://msoe.blackboard.com/webapps/blackboard/content/listContentEditable.jsp?content_id=_107501_1&course_id=_6447_1&mode=reset>. Here are the steps to upload your syllabus in Blackboard:
In most cases, you will already have updated your syllabus in Word. We recommend that you save the document as a PDF to post into your course to make sure that the students will see it exactly as you have created it. (Sometimes Word documents will not transfer unusual characters or spacing easily). Keep your Word document on file on your computer for easy updating next semester too.
Refer to the syllabus/schedules<https://msoe.blackboard.com/webapps/blackboard/content/listContentEditable.jsp?content_id=_107496_1&course_id=_6447_1&mode=reset> section for more explanation about the content needed in your syllabus.
When you are ready to post your document:
* On your computer, Save as a PDF. * In Blackboard, click on Build Content, and then select Add File. * This will allow you to browse your computer to select your PDF syllabus. * Click submit to complete the process. Join the conversation on Twitter at #EveryPageCountsMSOE. Find this and more on the new Technology & Apps <http://www.msoe.edu/campus-life/student-resources/information-technology/technology-and-apps/> page.

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Regular internet problem in the Tower
helpdesk-ticket.description:
Hello,
I'm up on the 14th floor in the tower and the internet connectivity has been really bad the lat 1-2 weeks. I have been calling ipconfig /release and ipconfig /renew about every 90 minutes. I generally have to renew twice with the following error appearing (varied if it is wi-fi or lan):
"An error occurred while renewing interface Local Area Connection 2 : The name specified in the network control block (NCB) is in use on a remote adapter. The NCB is the data."
This is with two different computers and both wi-fi and wired connections, so I don't think it is me. When I look at the connection chart there is a 'Walter" computer connected into router? That doesn't make much sense. I would really like to have a steady connection.
Just let me know if you need the MAC address or something...
Lisa Rebenitsch, Ph.D. Assistant Professor Electrical Engineering and Computer Science Dept.
[MSOE]<http://msoe.edu> (414) 277-2267<tel:%28414%29%20277-2267> rebenitsch@msoe.edu<mailto:rebenitsch@msoe.edu>

"An error occurred while renewing interface Local Area Connection 2 : The name specified in the network control block (NCB) is in use on a remote adapter. The NCB is the data."

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Rebenitsch,
If you are using a router in your room, we are unable to troubleshoot your personal router, as there are too many variables that go along with it. If you use the MSOE wireless, or plug a network cable directly from the wall to your device, can you replicate the issue?
If yes, your room port may be accidentally plugged into the network closet in a port designed for the cameras, or another network device. You should be unable to get the internet from that port entirely, but your device may be flipping between the wireless and wired IP addresses. If you can provide the MAC and the port number on your wall (usually [room number]-[port number], such as 1401-1) I can look up your device from here and determine which port you are in. If it's an incorrect port type, I can fix it remotely.
If your device uses your own router, or your own wireless, I would recommend factory resetting the device and changing the password. You should not be seeing unknown computers on your network, and your router may be compromised. While we don't forbid you to use your own wireless in the Tower, every additional wireless device near you will cause problems with each other, and with the MSOE provided wireless, and we strongly recommend disabling wireless on your router and using it only for wired access. Please use MSOE wireless instead. (The IP addresses used on commercial routers are blocked on our network, to prevent them from causing problems if configured incorrectly)
If any of this is confusing, let me know, and we can dispatch a Helpdesk tech over to take a look. I've been told I'm not the best person to convey complex ideas.
Thanks,
Paul Fabian
MSOE Director of IT Services
fabian@msoe.edu
(414) 277-2355

helpdesk-note.body:
Dr. Rebenitsch,
I have two possible scenarios I can think of at first glance. 1) your DNS settings in your IPv4 properties are set to us a manual address (192.168.1.1) instead of automatically getting the DNS from MSOE. You can check via this link: http://windows.microsoft.com/en-us/windows/change-tcp-ip-settings#1TC=windows-7 . 2) Someone either intentionally or unintentionally is trying to redirect DNS requests on your switch - they may be using a router that provides DNS information, and they have it hooked up incorrectly. I'll see if I can block that type of traffic from the switch if it's not sent from MSOE.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Carole Kasprzycki, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6072
With this error, the usual culprit is Email. Either Email on your phone or Email on your computer has an old password. There are other things that can hold on to old passwords and get your account locked out due to too many bad password attempts. A few of them are: Google Chrome, Wireless Networks, and other phone accounts. If clearing or updating these does not help, we can send someone to your office to investigate further.
Please let us know if this clearing any of these works.
James Windorff Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288

helpdesk-note.body:
So basically the answer was that the license that you have on MSOE’s server is not good for 17.3 because I can use 17.1 but if I upgrade then it says the license is wrong. When I click on the icon to open the software it prompts me to upgrade (for free) to fix known bugs and upgrade functionality.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Landon,
There are two APs in the tree lounge, one of the older 3610 units and one of the newest 3825. Both show around 10 users each, and both are showing normal speeds. Nothing in the logs indicate excessive packet loss or something similar. When we go to Tree Lounge and test with our devices, we do not experience a problem.
Any additional information that would help us trouble shoot is very helpful. Even where the user is standing, what device they are using, what time of day it happened - anything is useful. We try and duplicate the results but we have not been successful in this case.
Wireless access is an important part of IT service delivery and we take reports of poor performance seriously. In some cases it can be as simple as adding another Access Point (AP) but with load balancing and multiple AP's in place, even this can lead to a worse signal in some locations. With this information, I will mark this incident as resolved. Any reply to this incident will reopen it however. So if any additional information is provided we will respond to that. Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Landon,

There are two APs in the tree lounge, one of the older 3610 units and one of the newest 3825. Both show around 10 users each, and both are showing normal speeds.  Nothing in the logs indicate excessive packet loss or something similar.  When we go to Tree Lounge and test with our devices, we do not experience a problem.

Any additional information that would help us trouble shoot is very helpful.  Even where the user is standing, what device they are using, what time of day it happened - anything is useful.  We try and duplicate the results but we have not been successful in this case. 

Wireless access is an important part of IT service delivery and we take reports of poor performance seriously.  In some cases it can be as simple as adding another Access Point (AP) but with load balancing and multiple AP's in place, even this can lead to a worse signal in some locations.

With this information, I will mark this incident as resolved.  Any reply to this incident will reopen it however.  So if any additional information is provided we will respond to that.

Peter Pfister
Help Desk Coordinator
414.277.7202

When I go into MSOE community, I am able to log in and it indicates my email is kiltz@msoe.edu, but MSOE Community treats me like a visitor to the site with no access to any of the internal tools that staff may have. helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Kiltz,
Your MSOE account password has expired. Account passwords must be changed once every 90 days or they expire (they get locked). I will reset your password to the MSOE default so that you can log in. The default password is as follows:

helpdesk-ticket.description: User is requesting 4 static IP's for a CRON event that is saturday however they need the VPN friday. The team needs to practice on friday (the day they need the VPN) for the event. This request is because the RSOB is unavailable on friday. helpdesk-note.body:
Thomas,
I wont have an opportunity to call you, but if you could summarize what you need, I should be able to assist. Do you need 4 static IP addresses so that you can VPN to the boxes in RSOB? Will the boxes be in RSOB, because IP addresses are specific to building and floor, so I will need to know where these will be when you need them, or the static addresses wont work the way you expect.
Do you plan to use MSOE VPN (GlobalProtect) to reach these? If so, if the devices remain powered on and connected to the network, they should keep the dynamic IP automatically assigned to them through DHCP, and you should be able to reach them simply by logging on to VPN and using you application of choice to connect. If you plan to use another VPN, or need external internet access, firewall rules will need to be put in place, and I will need a list of application types and the ports they use to make a new firewall policy.
Let me know how I can help,
Paul Fabian Director of IT Services Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6165

From: helpdesk [mailto:helpdesk@msoe.edu]

To: Hill, Thomas <hillt@msoe.edu>
Subject: Re: [#INC-6165] VPN CRON
 
Thomas,
 
I wont have an opportunity to call you, but if you could summarize what you need, I should be able to assist. Do you need 4 static IP addresses so that you can VPN to the boxes in RSOB? Will the boxes be in RSOB, because IP addresses are specific to building and floor, so I will need to know where these will be when you need them, or the static addresses wont work the way you expect.
 
Do you plan to use MSOE VPN (GlobalProtect) to reach these? If so, if the devices remain powered on and connected to the network, they should keep the dynamic IP automatically assigned to them through DHCP, and you should be able to reach them simply by logging on to VPN and using you application of choice to connect. If you plan to use another VPN, or need external internet access, firewall rules will need to be put in place, and I will need a list of application types and the ports they use to make a new firewall policy.
 
Let me know how I can help,
 
Paul Fabian
Director of IT Services

Mitch Colton

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi Mitch Colton, Issue: http://helpdesk.msoe.edu/helpdesk/tickets/6195
On the school computers Windows 10 is not supported. If you upgrade it will also take you off the domain (printers and get programs will not work).
With regards to the position question, we are investigating it however do not as of now have any information to release.
I am marking this issue as resolved as this is all the information we have.
James Windorff Helpdesk Technician helpdesk@msoe.edu 414 277 7288

helpdesk-ticket.description:
Beth,
Noel Levitz can no longer support their Powerfaids extract and have asked me to work with our IT to develop an extract to send to them.
Please let me know when a good time for you to go over this data. After I send the data to Noel Levitz, they process the data and send a report back to MSOE. I typically send this file weekly.
Dawn asked for this report last week so I was hoping to send the file this week if possible.
Thanks,
Steve Midthun Assoc.Director of Financial Aid MSOE- Financial Aid Office (CC431) 1025 N Broadway Milwaukee, WI 53202 midthun@msoe.edu<mailto:midthun@msoe.edu> 414-277-7224
From: David Waite [mailto:David.Waite@ruffalonl.com] Sent: Monday, March 07, 2016 6:00 PM To: Midthun, Steven <Midthun@msoe.edu> Subject: RE: Fall 2015 enrolled list for Retention
Hi Steve, the files are attached, these are SQL scripts that would have to be opened with that program. The Create Awards View does just that, creates the view within PF’s and the extract pulls the data set we need for the ERMS analysis. These are generic scripts which likely would need to be modified to work specifically for (MSOE). We are working on getting some programming assistance in doing this and I will let you know when that team has been determined. Did you get a specific error when attempting to run the current extract? I’ve had a couple clients run the extract from last year and it ran okay, but that has not been the case for all.
David
From: Midthun, Steven [mailto:Midthun@msoe.edu] Sent: Monday, March 07, 2016 3:44 PM To: David Waite Subject: RE: Fall 2015 enrolled list for Retention
You can send to me for now. I will have to talk to my IT.
Thanks,
Steve Midthun Assoc.Director of Financial Aid MSOE- Financial Aid Office (CC431) 1025 N Broadway Milwaukee, WI 53202 midthun@msoe.edu<mailto:midthun@msoe.edu> 414-277-7224
From: David Waite [mailto:David.Waite@ruffalonl.com] Sent: Monday, March 07, 2016 11:55 AM To: Midthun, Steven <Midthun@msoe.edu<mailto:Midthun@msoe.edu>> Subject: RE: Fall 2015 enrolled list for Retention
Hi Steve,
Due to the loss of support of Foxpro and moving to a new software platform on my end we don’t have a PowerFAIDS extract similar to what we have had in the past which you could download and run. We have created two SQL scripts, the first will create a View in PF’s and the second an extract. They would need to be modified to “run” specifically for MSOE. We are working on getting some support for using these scripts and specifically setting them up. As soon as I hear back regarding that I will let you know. In the meantime would you like me to send the scripts we have created to you or someone on your IT staff?
David

helpdesk-note.body:
Thanks, Andy. I also received your voice message and appreciate the reply.
I’ve heard from Marty Handley that other faculty have had the same issue in S343. Dr. Meier also mentioned it to me. The problem is that, without a longer cable, it is not possible be in the center front and facing the students as one does a demo on the screens. So, I would indeed appreciate having the cable since it will let me be centrally located instead of having to move to the corner.
I wonder if it would be best to leave the cable in the room, either permanently attached or not, since it affects many faculty. But, if you think it would work better, I agree that me also bringing the extension cable with me is a good solution. It could be dropped off in my mailbox in L350 during regular business hours. There is no rush since I will not be in that room again until Wednesday.
Thank you very much!
-- Eric

But, if you think it would work better, I agree that me also bringing the extension cable with me is a good solution. Thank you very much!
 
-- Eric

I have one class in CC45, and the projector projects a very dull, hazy image.  I would not mind for most of my classes, but I am teaching art history the first time this quarter, and I really need to have a projector that projects a bright, clear image.  Could the projector be replaced with a better one, or would changing the bulb in the current projector fix the problem?
 
Please let me know what you can do.
 
Dr. Patrick J. Jung

helpdesk-ticket.subject: Wireless AP in MAGE Corner Not Working
helpdesk-ticket.description: One of the wireless APs in the MAGE corner is not working correctly, I am able to successfully ping the AP but cannot access anything else. See attached screenshot.
helpdesk-ticket.description-html: One of the wireless APs in the MAGE corner is not working correctly, I am able to successfully ping the AP but cannot access anything else. See attached screenshot.

helpdesk-note.body:
Hi hardenc,
The AP we provided to MAGE that was secured in a locked room is no longer reporting on the network. You may wish to ask around and see if the AP has been disconnected, moved, or removed, as it was dedicated to the area of the MAGE office. Is there someone from MAGE that we can speak to directly? The IP that you are able to ping is not the AP, it's the subnet gateway on the core in the datacenter. Unless the network core fails, or routing breaks, you will always be able to ping the subnet gateway of the subnet you are on.
We will swing by and take a look at the current wireless situation, as even with a low signal, you should be able to ping Google DNS, but it would put our mind at ease if we could manage the AP we provided.
Thanks,
Paul Fabian
MSOE Director of IT Services
fabian@msoe.edu
(414) 277-2355

helpdesk-ticket.description-html: I am attempting to download some files from off campus and am receiving terrible bandwidth right now.  The site is hosted at GoDaddy.com, and I am currently receiving 22 KiB/s ftp download from the site.

helpdesk-note.body: Hi Walter Schilling, Thank you for bringing this to our attention. That is a very slow file transfer but I am unsure what course of action to take. How was the rest of your network response on the laptop? Was the transfer speed the same after a reboot? I do not think there is anything inherently wrong with your laptops network configuration. Has it been changed recently? Did the speed change at all during the weekend? Please let me know any additional information that may help trouble shoot this issue. Peter Pfister Help Desk Coordinator 414.277.7202
helpdesk-note.body-html:
Hi Walter Schilling,

Thank you for bringing this to our attention.  That is a very slow file transfer but I am unsure what course of action to take.  How was the rest of your network response on the laptop?  Was the transfer speed the same after a reboot?  I do not think there is anything inherently wrong with your laptops network configuration.  Has it been changed recently?  Did the speed change at all during the weekend?  Please let me know any additional information that may help trouble shoot this issue.

Peter Pfister
Help Desk Coordinator
